00:41:36,227 --> 00:41:38,127
"'Don't stop! Don't ever stop."'

449
00:41:38,229 --> 00:41:40,026
-Hey, that's private.
-I hope so.

450
00:41:40,130 --> 00:41:42,394
It should never be made public.

451
00:41:43,767 --> 00:41:46,065
It's pitiful and sad.

452
00:41:46,437 --> 00:41:50,771
A hopelessly bad writer
buried in a cheap hotel on Bunker Hill.

453
00:41:52,209 --> 00:41:54,439
In Los Angeles, of all places.

454
00:41:58,482 --> 00:42:02,353
-They'll never read what you write.
-That's not really my writing.

455
00:42:02,520 --> 00:42:05,318
They won't even have a chance
to forget it.

456
00:42:05,422 --> 00:42:08,391
Say, what's going on?
Where did you come from?

457
00:42:08,926 --> 00:42:11,224
-Is this a gag?
-You're nobody.

458
00:42:12,129 --> 00:42:14,222
I might have been somebody,

459
00:42:16,333 --> 00:42:17,630
and here we are.

460
00:42:26,210 --> 00:42:30,476
Lady. Lady, you've got to sober up.

461
00:42:33,017 --> 00:42:35,212
How about a little fresh air?

462
00:42:36,987 --> 00:42:39,649
We could go out
and have a drink. Money.

463
00:42:45,629 --> 00:42:46,687
Lady?

464
00:42:48,299 --> 00:42:50,529
Good idea. Let's have a drink.

465
00:42:52,570 --> 00:42:56,267
You are gonna be so marvelous!
So wonderful!

466
00:42:56,373 --> 00:42:58,807
-My landlady.
-I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

467
00:43:01,478 --> 00:43:04,572
-Forget it, now. Let's just walk.
-Okay, but we're having a drink.

468
00:43:04,682 --> 00:43:06,741
I insist. Look, money!

469
00:43:06,850 --> 00:43:10,342
Okay, we'll have a drink.
Just put it back in your purse.

470
00:43:24,335 --> 00:43:27,099
-Hey, Mr. Bandini.
-Hi, Solomon. How's business?

471
00:43:27,204 --> 00:43:31,800
Till you showed up, Mr. Bandini, I had
more pinball machines than customers.

472
00:43:32,843 --> 00:43:35,437
-A short beer, am I right?
-And whiskey.

473
00:43:35,913 --> 00:43:37,505
Lots of whiskey.

474
00:43:39,450 --> 00:43:41,077
Does he know you?

475
00:43:41,819 --> 00:43:45,812
Your mouth, your wonderful mouth.
God, what a mouth.

476
00:43:45,923 --> 00:43:47,891
No, let's have a drink first.

477
00:43:56,233 --> 00:43:58,428
-What's wrong?
-You know what's wrong.

478
00:43:58,535 --> 00:44:02,062
-No, I don't.
-You're just like the rest of them.

479
00:44:02,373 --> 00:44:03,863
-You know!
-Know what?

480
00:44:03,974 --> 00:44:08,035
-That's why you won't kiss me!
-Here we go. One short beer.

481
00:44:08,912 --> 00:44:10,675
And double whiskey.

482
00:44:12,716 --> 00:44:15,082
-So who was it?
-Who was what?

483
00:44:15,185 --> 00:44:17,346
Who told you about my wounds?

484
00:44:17,721 --> 00:44:19,086
Your wounds?

485
00:44:22,459 --> 00:44:25,053
Do you have a nickel?
I love pinball machines.

486
00:44:25,162 --> 00:44:27,130
One game. Would you mind?

487
00:44:32,870 --> 00:44:35,896
-Whatever my darling wishes.
-Thank you.

488
00:44:45,582 --> 00:44:49,575
Solomon, could you come over here?
For some reason, it's on tilt.

489
00:44:49,987 --> 00:44:51,352
Play. Play.

490
00:44:53,223 --> 00:44:54,850
Who is that woman?

491
00:44:55,926 --> 00:44:57,188
Who knows?

492
00:44:58,662 --> 00:45:00,425
She was in a week before last,

493
00:45:00,531 --> 00:45:02,692
when you were talking
about Sinclair Lewis

494
00:45:02,800 --> 00:45:04,961
to that couple from Minnesota.

495
00:45:05,069 --> 00:45:08,800
-I didn't notice her.
-Well, she noticed you, believe you me.

496
00:45:09,640 --> 00:45:12,939
Listened to every word you said.
Every single word.

497
00:45:13,811 --> 00:45:17,303
-And when you left, she left.
-And what's she doing now?

498
00:45:22,119 --> 00:45:25,919
-Watching you like a prize dog.
-I gotta get out of here.

499
00:45:26,356 --> 00:45:28,517
Door opposite the men's room.

500
00:45:33,597 --> 00:45:37,124
Is everything all right, darling?
Do you need another nickel?

501
00:45:37,234 --> 00:45:39,896
No. No, I'm just gonna use...

502
00:46:08,098 --> 00:46:10,032
-Oh, my God!
-Darling.

503
00:46:10,968 --> 00:46:13,061
I took a cab and the door was open.

504
00:46:13,170 --> 00:46:14,762
Don't you think this has gone
far enough?

505
00:46:14,872 --> 00:46:17,102
"I see them in the lobbies of hotels.

506
00:46:17,207 --> 00:46:21,337
"I see them sunning in the parks
and limping out of little ugly churches,

507
00:46:21,445 --> 00:46:25,108
"dispossessed in this place
where the seasons never change."

508
00:46:27,317 --> 00:46:29,012
That's more like it.

509
00:46:29,453 --> 00:46:31,421
Will you please get out?

510
00:46:32,422 --> 00:46:35,050
You're my darling,
and you're going to love me.

511
00:46:35,159 --> 00:46:38,287
Some other time. I think you better go.
I mean it.

512
00:46:44,601 --> 00:46:46,569
I know how I revolt you,

513
00:46:47,538 --> 00:46:50,132
that you know what my clothes
are covering up.

514
00:46:50,240 --> 00:46:52,868
Know what?
I don't even know your name.

515
00:46:54,178 --> 00:46:55,611
Vera Rivkin.

516
00:46:56,480 --> 00:46:58,380
Back East I had a real life

517
00:46:58,482 --> 00:47:00,973
and friends who knew about
H.L. Mencken

518
00:47:01,084 --> 00:47:03,211
and Edna St. Vincent Millay.

519
00:47:04,354 --> 00:47:06,219
Now I'm a housekeeper.

520
00:47:07,124 --> 00:47:09,718
I work for a nice Jewish family
in Long Beach.

521
00:47:09,827 --> 00:47:12,796
I'm tired. Tired of housekeeping.

522
00:47:14,498 --> 00:47:17,899
Then one day, I saw you at Solomon's,

523
00:47:19,336 --> 00:47:21,099
and I heard you talk.

524
00:47:22,639 --> 00:47:25,073
And I went and I bought your story.

525
00:47:25,843 --> 00:47:27,333
And I read it.

526
00:47:29,947 --> 00:47:32,415
And I felt that you were someone

527
00:47:33,150 --> 00:47:36,711
who could look at me
and see me for what I am.

528
00:47:37,387 --> 00:47:39,287
So I followed you home.

529
00:47:39,923 --> 00:47:41,254
So stupid.

530
00:47:42,526 --> 00:47:43,754
Hopeless.

531
00:47:46,496 --> 00:47:49,954
But I'm really a good person.
Honestly, I am.

532
00:47:54,071 --> 00:47:55,095
Here.

533
00:47:56,106 --> 00:47:57,164
Thank you.

534
00:47:58,141 --> 00:48:01,838
-What do you want me to do?
-Tell me I'm like other women.

535
00:48:01,945 --> 00:48:05,346
-Tell me I'm beautiful, please.
-But you are beautiful.

536
00:48:06,416 --> 00:48:07,883
Really, you are.

537
00:48:08,151 --> 00:48:10,381
This is just a childish obsession.

538
00:48:10,487 --> 00:48:14,446
You know, maybe a hangover
from the mumps. I don't know.

539
00:48:15,058 --> 00:48:17,583
Plenty of men would give anything...

540
00:48:18,629 --> 00:48:20,620
Let me show you something.

541
00:48:23,800 --> 00:48:28,260
-You don't have to show me anything.
-You're going to see it for yourself.

542
00:48:30,941 --> 00:48:32,533
Undo this, please.

543
00:48:34,678 --> 00:48:37,272
Look, you've convinced me, all right?

544
00:49:05,609 --> 00:49:08,476
Yeah. Yeah, I thought so.

545
00:49:15,285 --> 00:49:17,219
You know all about them.

546
00:49:18,956 --> 00:49:21,823
So what's the fuss? That's nothing.

547
00:49:31,501 --> 00:49:33,332
Tell that to my husband.

548
00:49:34,972 --> 00:49:37,497
"Deformed, disfigured,

549
00:49:38,976 --> 00:49:40,273
"disgusting."

550
00:49:41,244 --> 00:49:42,939
That's what he said.

551
00:49:53,190 --> 00:49:54,350
I say,

552
00:49:55,425 --> 00:49:57,052
you're beautiful.

553
00:50:15,178 --> 00:50:16,475
Excuse me.

554
00:50:20,250 --> 00:50:22,241
I'm so sorry. I'm sorry.

555
00:50:22,686 --> 00:50:25,712
I'm so sorry. I don't know
what was in my head. I just...

556
00:50:25,822 --> 00:50:28,950
Take it easy.
I'll wait outside so you can...

557
00:50:30,394 --> 00:50:31,827
Take it easy.

558
00:50:57,020 --> 00:50:58,317
<i>"Dear Boy,</i>

559
00:50:59,289 --> 00:51:02,725
<i>"of course I should have known</i>
<i>you'd have a girlfriend.</i>

560
00:51:02,959 --> 00:51:04,824
<i>"Is she very beautiful?</i>

561
00:51:05,362 --> 00:51:06,989
<i>"She's very lucky.</i>

562
00:51:08,365 --> 00:51:10,595
<i>"Is she also kind and generous?</i>

563
00:51:11,668 --> 00:51:15,900
<i>"Would she ever allow you to come</i>
<i>to Long Beach, if only for an hour?"</i>

564
00:51:21,678 --> 00:51:22,940
<i>I woke up relieved to think</i>

565
00:51:23,046 --> 00:51:26,106
<i>there were other possibilities in life</i>
<i>besides Camilla.</i>

566
00:51:26,216 --> 00:51:29,083
<i>Maybe Vera was a little crazy,</i>
<i>but like she said about herself,</i>

567
00:51:29,186 --> 00:51:30,619
<i>she was a good person.</i>

568
00:51:30,720 --> 00:51:33,814
<i>We'd read the same books,</i>
<i>spoke the same language</i>

569
00:51:33,924 --> 00:51:36,950
<i>and she was capable</i>
<i>of appreciating my writing.</i>

570
00:51:37,060 --> 00:51:41,292
<i>Suddenly, I felt better about myself.</i>
<i>I was once again, Arturo Bandini,</i>

571
00:51:41,398 --> 00:51:44,663
<i>lover of man and beast alike,</i>
<i>and afraid of nothing.</i>

572
00:51:45,001 --> 00:51:48,528
Mr. Bandini! Hey! Bandini!

573
00:51:49,473 --> 00:51:51,941
It's Sammy,
the bartender at the Columbia.

574
00:51:52,042 --> 00:51:54,442
-Yeah. Sammy White.
-Yeah.

575
00:51:55,445 --> 00:51:58,608
-Camilla says you've been published.
-What of it?

576
00:51:58,782 --> 00:52:01,876
I was thinking about getting into
that line of work.

577
00:52:01,985 --> 00:52:05,182
-Publishing?
-No, writing stories like you.

578
00:52:05,589 --> 00:52:09,958
Bartending and the damp nights don't
seem to agree with me much anymore.

579
00:52:10,894 --> 00:52:13,624
Looking to find something I can do
pretty much anywhere.

580
00:52:13,730 --> 00:52:15,425
Like writing stories.

581
00:52:15,532 --> 00:52:17,727
Yeah, well, good luck to you, Sammy.

582
00:52:17,834 --> 00:52:20,234
Yeah, I was hoping
you could give me a few pointers.

583
00:52:20,337 --> 00:52:23,397
And that magazine
with "The Little Dog Laughing" in it,

584
00:52:23,507 --> 00:52:26,169
you wouldn't happen to have
a spare copy?

585
00:52:27,043 --> 00:52:29,375
I'd sure like to read your story.

586
00:52:30,981 --> 00:52:33,677
I know I got one in here somewhere.

587
00:52:41,091 --> 00:52:43,582
Thank you, Arturo. It's a real honor.

588
00:52:43,693 --> 00:52:48,027
Like I said, I was hoping you could
give me some pointers about writing.

589
00:52:49,533 --> 00:52:52,195
If there's anything I can do for you,
you let me know.

590
00:52:52,302 --> 00:52:54,668
Sounds like you've got something
in mind.

591
00:52:54,771 --> 00:52:58,434
Well, thought you might like
a little advice about Camilla.

592
00:52:59,376 --> 00:53:03,710
That's real white of you, Sammy,
but I think I can handle the situation.

593
00:53:04,114 --> 00:53:05,411
Okey-dokey.

594
00:53:07,017 --> 00:53:11,147
But you know what they say,
"Never a horse that couldn't be rode,

595
00:53:11,254 --> 00:53:13,814
"never a cowboy
that couldn't be throwed."

596
00:53:13,924 --> 00:53:17,883
And Camilla's one tough little pony.
She's got a real hard mouth on her.

597
00:53:17,994 --> 00:53:20,929
"A real hard mouth."
Interesting turn of phrase.

598
00:53:21,331 --> 00:53:24,095
You're too nice to that girl, Mr. Bandini.

599
00:53:25,202 --> 00:53:26,829
-Too nice?
-Way too nice.

600
00:53:26,937 --> 00:53:29,405
You don't understand Mexican women.

601
00:53:30,140 --> 00:53:33,200
-Oh, Mexican women are different.
-No, sir.

602
00:53:34,244 --> 00:53:36,906
They're like most women,
except more so.

603
00:53:37,847 --> 00:53:39,815
You let up on them,
they're all gonna take advantage.

604
00:53:39,916 --> 00:53:41,543
But you ease up on that little spic,

605
00:53:41,651 --> 00:53:43,915
she gonna peg you
for a lily-livered gringo

606
00:53:44,020 --> 00:53:47,183
and buck you out of the saddle
before you're in it.

607
00:53:47,791 --> 00:53:52,728
A horse with a hard mouth
don't feel the bit, Arturo.

608
00:53:52,829 --> 00:53:55,992
So, keep them on a tight rein,

609
00:53:57,033 --> 00:54:01,129
never let them forget
who's boss for a second. No trick to it.

610
00:54:01,504 --> 00:54:03,665
Ride them hard and it's easy.

611
00:54:04,241 --> 00:54:08,644
Well, Sammy,
sounds like you know your horseflesh.

612
00:54:08,745 --> 00:54:10,679
Yeah, I hope so, Arturo.

613
00:54:11,715 --> 00:54:13,683
I'm gonna write Westerns.

614
00:54:17,621 --> 00:54:19,282
By the way, <i>amigo,</i>

615
00:54:22,192 --> 00:54:24,854
Camilla's one pony
who's worth the ride.

616
00:54:33,036 --> 00:54:34,765
I'm glad to see you.

617
00:54:35,138 --> 00:54:36,162
Why?

618
00:54:37,807 --> 00:54:38,831
Okay.

619
00:54:41,444 --> 00:54:44,208
Sammy told me
you were really nice to him.

620
00:54:44,881 --> 00:54:48,373
I was beginning to think
you couldn't be nice to anyone.

621
00:54:51,888 --> 00:54:54,755
-Can I get you something?
-Where is Sammy tonight?

622
00:54:54,858 --> 00:54:56,587
-He left.
-Went home?

623
00:54:57,093 --> 00:55:00,790
To the desert for a while.
He hasn't been feeling real good.

624
00:55:00,964 --> 00:55:03,398
-What's the matter with him?
-Camilla.

625
00:55:04,200 --> 00:55:05,565
TB, I think.

626
00:55:18,081 --> 00:55:21,050
Here. You can start with this.

627
00:55:21,818 --> 00:55:26,118
-Sammy has tuberculosis.
-Yeah. Tough break, huh?

628
00:55:26,723 --> 00:55:28,281
We all gotta go.

629
00:55:35,365 --> 00:55:37,424
What are you talking about?

630
00:55:37,901 --> 00:55:41,234
-He won't live long.
-How dare you say something like that!

631
00:55:41,338 --> 00:55:43,932
So how are all your other boyfriends?

632
00:55:44,040 --> 00:55:45,507
I haven't got any other boyfriends!

633
00:55:45,608 --> 00:55:48,076
Sure. Forgive an incautious remark.

634
00:55:49,379 --> 00:55:51,244
Could I have the check?

635
00:55:52,849 --> 00:55:55,647
No charge. It's on Sammy.

636
00:56:09,733 --> 00:56:10,927
Bandini.

637
00:56:17,407 --> 00:56:19,534
You don't have to pay
to be a smart aleck.

638
00:56:19,642 --> 00:56:23,908
Besides, if it cost more than half a buck,
you couldn't afford to be one.

639
00:56:24,013 --> 00:56:26,709
You're very funny.
Sammy writing your dialogue?

640
00:56:27,817 --> 00:56:31,218
Why do you have to be so mean?

641
00:56:31,321 --> 00:56:32,845
Mean? Me?

642
00:56:33,423 --> 00:56:35,254
I'm anything but mean.

643
00:56:36,126 --> 00:56:38,890
I'm a lover, my dear girl.
Equally fond of man and beast alike.

644
00:56:38,995 --> 00:56:41,429
You can't be mean
and be a great writer.

